faqs:
  - q: "What is the Federal Tort Claims Act (FTCA)?"
    a: "The FTCA is the federal law that allows individuals to sue the United States government for injuries caused by federal employees acting within the scope of their employment — including doctors and nurses at VA hospitals and military facilities."
  - q: "How long do I have to file an FTCA claim?"
    a: "You must file an administrative claim with the appropriate federal agency within 2 years of the incident. If denied, you have 6 months to file a lawsuit in federal court. These deadlines are strict."
  - q: "Can I sue a VA doctor directly?"
    a: "No. Under the FTCA, the United States is substituted as the defendant. You cannot sue individual federal employees — your claim is against the government."
  - q: "Do FTCA cases go to a jury?"
    a: "No. FTCA cases are tried before a federal judge only — there is no jury trial. This makes the quality of your legal argument and evidence presentation even more critical."
